kkow!”: Bird Debates and Chaucer’s “Manciple’s Tale” -- tChapter 14 Perceval’s Mare -- tChapter 15 Gower’s Aristotelian Legacy: Reading Responsibility in the Confessio Amantis and the Lytle Bibell of Knyghthod -- tChapter 16 “The Prioress’s Tale” and Vernacular Devotion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThomas Hahn’s work laid the foundations for medieval romance studies to embrace the study of alterity and hybridity within Middle English literature. His contributions to scholarship brought Robin Hood studies into the critical mainstream, normalized the study of historically marginalized literature and peoples, and encouraged scholars to view medieval readers as actively encountering others and exploring themselves. This volume employs his methodologies – careful attention to texts and their contexts, cross-cultural readings, and theoretically-informed analysis – to highlight the literary culture of late medieval England afresh. Addressing long-established canonical works such as Chaucer, Christine de Pizan, and Malory alongside understudied traditions and manuscripts, this book will be of interest to literary scholars of the later Middle Ages who, like Hahn, work across boundaries of genre, tradition, and chronology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory. 0aRomance-language literaturexHistory. 4aLesekultur. 4aMarginalisierung. 4aMittelalterliche Literatur. 4aMittelenglisch. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMarginalization.  aMedieval Romance.  aMiddle English.  aReading Culture.1 aColetti, Theresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaught, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuber